<ArticleLayout
  title="Baby Bath Time: What You Need Close By"
  description="Prepare towels, wash items, clean clothes and the room before bathing a baby, with water safety and storage in mind."
  category="Nursery & Kids"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  dateModified="2026-07-19"
  faqs={faqs}
  readingTime="6 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/Nursery-kids.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy nursery with soft light, baby storage and everyday care items"
>
  <p>
    Once a baby is in the bath, the towel in the next room is no longer within reach. Set out
    the towel, clean nappy, clothes and wash cloths before running the water so the whole routine
    can happen without stepping away.
  </p>
  <p>
    That preparation matters far more than a long row of baby bath products. Most households
    need only a few washing items, a safe place to bathe the baby and a clear route from bathing
    to drying and dressing.
  </p>
  <p>
    For the broader baby setup, visit <a href="/categories/nursery-kids/">Nursery & Kids</a> or the
    <a href="/guides/nursery-essentials-for-australian-homes/">nursery essentials guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Supervision comes before the setup</h2>
  <p>
    An adult needs to supervise bath time from start to finish. The
    <a href="https://www.productsafety.gov.au/consumers/keep-baby-safe/bathe-and-change-baby-safely" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ACCC Product Safety bathing and changing guide</a>{" "}
    says to keep at least one hand supporting the baby, never leave the baby alone or in the care
    of another child, and take the baby with you if you must leave the room.
  </p>
  <p>
    A bath aid does not replace hands-on supervision. Read the warnings and instructions for any
    baby bath, support, seat, thermometer, mat or other accessory, use it only as intended and stop
    using it if it is damaged.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you are unsure about bathing a newborn or caring for a baby's skin, ask your midwife,
    child health nurse, GP or another qualified health professional.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan the route from water to clothes</h2>
  <p>
    Walk through the routine before buying storage or accessories. The bathing spot may be only
    one step from the change area, yet the arrangement can still be awkward if the towel is behind
    you or clean clothes are buried in a drawer.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Where will the baby be bathed?</li>
    <li>Who will usually handle bath time?</li>
    <li>Can that person reach the towel, nappy, clothes and wash items without moving away?</li>
    <li>Is there a clear, stable place to dry and dress the baby?</li>
    <li>Where will wet cloths, towels and clothes go?</li>
    <li>Can the area be reset without blocking the rest of the room?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If the answers require several trips between the bathroom, nursery and laundry, move the
    supplies before adding another product.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose a bathing spot that works when wet</h2>
  <p>
    A baby bath may be used in a bathroom, laundry or another location that meets the product
    instructions. Look beyond whether the bath fits. The surface needs to be stable, the room
    needs adequate light and warmth, and the filled bath must be manageable without unsafe lifting
    or awkward emptying.
  </p>
  <p>Also check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether towels and clean clothes can be kept close</li>
    <li>whether splashes can be cleaned without leaving a slippery route</li>
    <li>whether the bath and accessories can drain and dry between uses</li>
    <li>whether older children, pets or household traffic will get in the way</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The best location is the one where an adult can stay with the baby and keep control of the
    whole routine, not necessarily the room that looks most suitable in a photograph.
  </p>

  <h2>Set out only what you will use</h2>
  <p>
    Put the supplies within arm's reach before the baby goes near the water. The exact list depends
    on the baby's needs and any advice from a health professional, but it may include:
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>a towel or hooded towel</li>
    <li>a clean nappy</li>
    <li>clean clothes or pyjamas</li>
    <li>one or two wash cloths</li>
    <li>gentle baby wash if used</li>
    <li>nappy cream if part of the routine</li>
    <li>any items recommended by your health professional</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Keep bottles away from the edge where they can be knocked into the water. A
    <a href="/guides/nappy-change-station-checklist/">nappy change setup</a>{" "}
    nearby can make the dressing stage easier, provided everything remains reachable while the
    baby is supervised.
  </p>

  <h2>Prepare the drying area first</h2>
  <p>
    Open the towel, nappy and clothes before the bath begins. Clear the change surface and decide
    where wet items will land so you are not trying to unfold clothing or shift clutter while
    holding the baby.
  </p>
  <p>
    Afterwards, towels and cloths need room to dry rather than remaining in a heap or sealed
    container. If the bathroom already struggles with damp towels, the
    <a href="/guides/towel-storage-what-to-measure-before-buying-rails-hooks-or-shelves/">towel storage guide</a>{" "}
    covers rail space, airflow and shared bathrooms.
  </p>

  <h2>Buy for the routine, not the product list</h2>
  <p>
    A caddy, support or compact bath can solve a particular problem, but each item also needs to
    be cleaned, dried and stored. Before buying, check:
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>the product warnings, instructions and intended use</li>
    <li>whether it suits the baby's age, size and stage</li>
    <li>how it will be cleaned and dried between uses</li>
    <li>where it will live when the bathroom is needed by someone else</li>
    <li>whether it solves a problem you have actually encountered</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Start with fewer items and add something only when the routine shows why it is needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Wet items need an exit plan</h2>
  <p>
    Towels, wash cloths, bath supports and toys should be able to drain and dry. Storage that sits
    in the splash zone or traps water may make the area harder to clean rather than easier to use.
  </p>
  <p>
    Bath toys are optional, particularly for very young babies. As they enter the routine, choose
    age-appropriate items that can be cleaned and dried without trapping water. The number of
    towels and cloths you need likewise depends on washing frequency and drying space, not a fixed
    nursery checklist.
  </p>

  <h2>Shared and rented bathrooms need a reset plan</h2>
  <p>
    In a shared bathroom, baby items need somewhere to go once the bath is over. A small caddy or
    basket may be easier to carry out than fixed storage that crowds the shower, basin or toilet.
    The <a href="/categories/bathroom/">Bathroom</a> category has more help with towel drying and
    storage in busy rooms.
  </p>
  <p>
    Renters should check the lease before adding hooks or shelves. Portable caddies, freestanding
    towel racks and baskets may avoid permanent changes, but adhesive and suction products still
    need a suitable surface and can leave damage. See the
    <a href="/guides/renter-friendly-bathroom-storage-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">bathroom storage guide for renters</a>{" "}
    before fixing anything to tiles, paint or cabinetry.
  </p>

  <h2>Before the baby goes near the water</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Is an adult ready to supervise the whole time?</li>
    <li>Is the bath stable, undamaged and being used according to its instructions?</li>
    <li>Are the towel, nappy, clothes and wash items within arm's reach?</li>
    <li>Is the drying and dressing area clear?</li>
    <li>Can wet items drain or go straight to the laundry afterwards?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If something has been forgotten, collect it before the bath begins. Once bathing is under way,
    the baby stays with the supervising adult.
  </p>

  <h2>A small routine is easier to control</h2>
  <p>
    Baby bath time does not need an elaborate setup. It needs active supervision, supplies within
    reach and a clear place to dry and dress the baby afterwards.
  </p>
  <p>
    Add products only when they solve a problem in that sequence. For help keeping the wider first
    months setup equally grounded, see <a href="/guides/newborn-essentials/">Newborn Essentials</a>.
  </p>

